The "bloat" in .EXE files is caused by the many dependancies within VCL
and by the RTTI data that VCL is dependant of.  It also is the RTTI that 
makes VCL as versatile and powerful as it is.

You will see that the "bloat" size vs. project size factor improves with
the size of the project.  I.e. the larger the project is, the lesser will
the "bloat" impact be.  You may also tune away some of the RTTI 
information, if you really want to.

Delphi enables us to create complex database applications in a fraction
of the time it would have taken, using the Paradox engine.  Delphi has
cut the GUI developement time to next to nothing.  

The online/printed documentation that comes with Delphi is sufficient to 
get you started and if you need more info, you would dive into the RTL/VCL 
source.  My printed docs occupies a lot of shelf space and is seldom used.
I prefer searchable online docs (if only all doc was available to the
Microsoft Developers Network CD browser :-) ).

IMHO, although there are a few rough edges to Delphi, the advantages of
its features dwarf the disadvantages.  For writing DLL's, it's #1.
The clarity and simplicity of the new Object Pascal gives you unlimited
power (well, nearly) without falling into some of the C++ pitfalls.

I only see two real problems with Delphi:

  - Where is the standalone Debugger?
  - Where are the profiling tools?
  - Will I be able to take a vacation without withdrawal symptoms? :-)

